passages.text: USA | Dept. Stores & Specialty Softlines
**Equity Research** August 28, 2025
Model Update: Q2 and FY25 Guide Above Ests;Investments Still Ahead

Q2 results were well ahead of expectations. Macro and tougher comps in 2H limited FY guide increases, but were still above Street ests. FY comps expected in the 2.5% to +3.5% range (+2.1% cons). EPS raised above ests, and OM% increased and in line w/ cons. Co gained share in mass and prestige, and sales growth seems to have steadied, but OM% levg limited by ongoing investments.PT = $550.

**Q2 Above Expectations:** Comp sales of +6.7% (+3.7% transactions, +2.9% ticket) were above Street ests for +2.9% and ahead of buyside ests for 4%-5%. GM% 39.2% (+90 bps Y/Y) was also above 38.1% cons. SG&A rate at 26.6% (+130bps Y/Y) was roughly in line w/ cons. OM% of 12.4% beat ests of 11.4% but was -50bps vs. PY. EPS of $5.78 was above $5.10 cons.

**Beauty Consumer Still Engaged:** Ulta reported that engagement in beauty and wellness remains healthy, even as shoppers stay mindful of everyday expenses and pricing trends. Beauty enthusiasts are strongly engaged in the category and continue to prioritize their regimens, supporting its resilience. By segment, fragrance again led the portfolio with robust DD% growth, skin care and wellness were +HSD%, hair care generated +MSD% comps, and makeup also delivered +MSD% comps, with both mass and prestige positive.

**OM% Expansion Seems Capped for Now:** Given the comp level well above co's target 3-4% algo, we were looking for a clearer path to margin expansion. ULTA remains focused on making investments in order to maintain share in an intensifying competitive landscape, and to re-accelerate share growth. Co expressed they believe 12% OM% is normalized, and the 14-15% ULTA once held was in a different operating enviro. We view current 20x P/E as fair vs. peaks of 25x-30x when the co.was growing DD% and at mid-teens OM%.

**Target Partnership:** As previously announced, ULTA's shop-in-shop partnership with Target will end in August 2026. Mgmt. sized that the royalty revenue from the Target partnership was "well below" 1% of net sales in FY24. If we asstthe 0.5%, and at a 65% flow through per mgmt., this implies ~$0.60 of annualized EPS, which we believe would grow this year. ULTA should be able to recapture at least a portion of these sales at its own stores, which would limit the headwind, although OM% will be slightly pressur

**FY Guide Raised Above Street:** FY25 comp sales guide for +2.5% to +3.5% was raised from 0% to 1.5%, above Street ests for +2.1%. Net sales are expected between $12.0B and $12.1B (from $11.5B-$11.7B), above Street ests for $11.8B. EPS guide for $23.85 to $24.30 (raised from $22.65 to $23.2B) was above cons of $23.77. OM% increased to 11.9%-12.0% from 11.7%-11.8% range, in line w/ ests for 12.0%.

- Underlying beauty category growth robust, but competitive pressure from increased points of distribution.- Possibility of increased promotion could push out investment timeline.- Co still well-positioned in current macro environment, given broad price mix.- Market share pressure driven by brand composition.- UB Media margin benefits oppty remains to offset investment in e-comm & tech, but still nascent.
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View

- LSD's comps (below the industry growth M/HSD).- EPS growth including buybacks.- Specialty retail share remains fragmented, and challenged by e-comm and other channels.- Co. investing continues placing pressure on margins, but driving LT top-line stabilization.- FY26E EPS: \(26.91; Target Multiple: \sim 21x; Price Target:\) 550

- Comps move to \(\sim 4\%\) on cycle or share- Composition of sales blends between products & services; margin gains- Company reframes \(\sim 38M\) member CRM as personalization gateway for brands & content; introduces shoppable content; monetization \(\) 3\(\) 5 EPS- FY26E EPS: \(27.20; Target Multiple: \sim 23x; Price Target:\) 625

- Comp rates decelerate to roughly flat- Investment spend deleverages- Sales mix remains unfavorable- New service adoption initiatives fail to convert- Traffic shifts to online; store fallout- FY26E EPS: \(21.70. Target Multiple: \sim 17x; Price Target:\) 380

Top Material Issues: (1) Energy Management: It is becoming increasingly important for companies to manage their overall energy efficiency and their access to alternative energy sources. Efficiency in this area can have financial implications through direct cost savings. (2) Product Design & Lifecycle Management: Companies that effectively manage the sustainability of packaging & sourcing of materials may be better positioned to capture shifting consumer demand and avoid regulation related to producer responsibility.

Company Targets: (1) Reduce absolute Scope 1 & 2 GHG emissions \(90\%\) by 2030 and absolute Scope 3 GHG emissions covering use of sold products \(28\%\) by 2030, from a 2019 base year. (2) By 2027, \(68\%\) of Ulta Beauty's suppliers by emissions will have science- based targets.
Qs to Mgmt: (1) What is the margin effect of a larger sustainable product offering? (2) How will this assortment flow through to pricing for customers?
ESG Sector Deep Dive: Multiline Retail

- Sales: Sustained underlying demand despite macro pressure on consumer- Sales: Market share advancement despite intensifying competition- Sales: Potential beauty replenishment or trend cycle- Margins: Mitigation of margin drag from e-comm & investments- Aug Profit Stream: UB Media grows to ad business of size at \(80\% + 0M\%\) - Cash Flow: Strong CF post investment catch up; buyback

SpaceNK Acquisition: Mgmt provided further detail on the SpaceNK acquisition. SpaceNK operates 83 stores across the U.K. and Ireland as well as an online platform. Co will continue to operate as a stand- alone subsidiary under its current CEO, and Lightfoot. Strategically, Ulta sees SpaceNK as a platform to share best practices, particularly in the estate, high- street retailing, and accel int' expansion with limited capital intensity. The purchase was funded with cash on hand and borrowings under Ulta's existing credit facility, and mgmt noted that the transaction is not material to consolidated financials. Only one week of SpaceNK's performance is included in Q2. Ulta recorded \(\sim \$ 7M\) of onetime transaction expenses in SG&A related to the acquisition. Management has also increased FY25 sales and SG&A guidance to reflect SpaceNK's contribution.

Model Update: We updated our model for the increased FY25 guidance. Sales move to \(\) 12.0B\(from\) \ \(11.7B\) . FY25 EPS to \(\) 24.19\(from\) \ \(23.54\) . Our PT is \(\) 550\(based on\) \sim 21x \(FY26 EPS.\)
Exhibit 1 - ULTA Income Statement

Ulta BeautyULTA is a beauty retailer that carries prestige, mass, salon products and salon services all under one roof. The company combines aspects of a specialty retailer with a single destination status, offering over 21,000 products across the categories of cosmetics, fragrance, haircare, skincare, bath and body and professionally licensed salon products, including a full- service salon at each store. Stores are located in high- traffic, off- mall locations. ULTA maintains approximately 1,500 stores in the United States.
We value ULTA shares using FY2 P/E. Risks include comp rate variability, inventory and markdowns/promos, competition, and channel shift.

Amazon.com, IncValuation: Our \(\) 265\(PT is based on\) \sim 16x\(2026E EV/EBITDA. Risks: Ongoing need to invest keeps a lid on margin expansion; regulatory pressure leads to increasing costs; macroeconomic headwinds cause top - line growth to slow.

Target Corp.Our \(\) 115\(PT is based on F26 P/E of 15x and EV/EBITDA of\) \sim 8x\$ . Risks include increased competition from online and other brick- and- mortar retailers, heavy promotions to drive traffic, discretionary exposure, and higher/lower costs related to wages, transportation, and/or logistics expense.

Explanation of Jefferies RatingsBuy - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of 15% or more within a 12- month period. Hold - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of plus 15% or minus 10% within a 12- month period.

Underperform - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of minus \(10\%\) or less within a 12- month period. The expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) for Buy rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10 is 20\%\) or more within a 12- month period as these companies are typically more volatile than the overall stock market. For Hold rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10, the expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) is plus or minus 20\% with a 12 - month period. For Underperform rated securities with an average security price consistently below\) 10, the expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) is minus 20\% or less within a 12 - month period.

The price targets are based on several methodologies, which may include, but are not restricted to, analyses of market risk, growth rate, revenue stream, discounted cash flow (DCF), EBITDA, EPS, cash flow (CF), free cash flow (FCF), EV/EBITDA, P/E, PE/growth, P/CF, P/FCF, premium (discount)/average group EV/EBITDA, premium (discount)/average group P/E, sum of the parts, net asset value, dividend returns, and return on equity (ROE) over the next 12 months.

Jefferies Franchise Picks include stock selections from among the best stock ideas from our equity analysts over a 12 month period. Stock selection is based on fundamental analysis and may take into account other factors such as analyst conviction, differentiated analysis, a favorable risk/reward ratio and investment themes that Jefferies analysts are recommending. Jefferies Franchise Picks will include only Buy rated stocks and the number can vary depending on analyst recommendations for inclusion. Stocks will be added as new opportunities arise and removed when the reason for inclusion changes, the stock has met its desired return, if it is no longer rated Buy and/or if it triggers a stop loss. Stocks having 120 day volatility in the bottom quartile of S&P stocks will continue to have a 15% stop loss, and the remainder will have a 20% stop. Franchise Picks are not intended to represent a recommended portfolio of stocks and is not sector based, but we may note where we believe a Pick falls within an investment style such as growth or value.
